x`) and `X^{τ m} i = X i`. Hence, `X x → X i`.\n\nBut Lean's definition of `Function.RightContinuous` uses filters, so we need a filter-based approach.\n\n#### Formal Approach (Step-by-Step)\n1. From `hX`, obtain `τ`, `hτ_is_localizing`, and the right-continuity of the stopped processes.\n2. For any fixed `ω` in the set where all `τ n` are `⊤` (which is eventually the case a.e.), we have that `X^{τ n} = X`.\n   - But this is not correct: actually, `τ n` tends to `⊤`, but it doesn't mean `τ n = ⊤` for any finite `n`.\n   - Better: For any fixed `i : ι`, we can find `n` such that `τ n ≥ i` a.e. \n\n3. Actually, perhaps it's easier to reason as follows:\n   - For each `i : ι`, there exists `n` such that `τ n ≥ i` a.e.\n   - For this `n`, the stopped process `X^{τ n}` is right-continuous a.e.\n   - The function `X^{τ n}` coincides with `X` on `[i, ∞)` (because `τ n ≥ i`).\n   - Right continuity of `X^{τ n}` at `i` implies right continuity of `X` at `i`.\n\nBut Lean’s `Function.RightContinuous` is about all filters, so perhaps we need to do something else.\n\n#### More Formal Approach:\n1. For each `ω`, and for each `i : ι`, we can find an `n` such that `τ n ω ≥ i`. (Because `τ n → ⊤`, for each `ω`, `τ n ω → ⊤`.)\n   - However, we don’t have this directly in Lean because `Tendsto` for `ι` is not directly available.\n\nBut actually, perhaps not:\nWe can use that for any `i : ι`, `∃ n, ∀ m ≥ n, i ≤ τ m` (a.e.). \n\nAlternatively, since `ι` is a linear order and `τ n → ⊤`, for any `i : ι`, there exists an `n` such that `i ≤ τ n`.\n\nBut perhaps we can instead reason in terms of the pushforward:\n\n#### Using the Filter Definition of Right Continuity\n\nFor any `i : ι`, we want to show that `X · ω` is right continuous at `i`.\n\nThis means that for any neighborhood `V` of `X i ω`, there exists a neighborhood `U` of `i` in the right filter such that for any `j ∈ U`, `X j ω ∈ V`.\n\nGiven that `X^{τ n} · ω` is right-continuous, and for `n` such that `τ n ≥ i`, then for `j ≥ i`