      "5: Formal Proof Sketch\n\n1. Extract the localizing sequence `τ` from `hX`.\n2. Use that for `P`-a.e. `ω`, `τ n ω → ∞` to deduce that for any `x`, there exists `N` such that for all `n ≥ N`, `x < τ n ω`.\n3. Use the fact that for each `n`, `y ↦ X(y)(ω)` is right-continuous on `y ≤ τ n ω`.\n4. To compute `lim_{y → x+} X(y)(ω)`, take `n` sufficiently large that `x < τ n ω`, so that `y → X(y)(ω)` coincides with `y → (if y < τ n ω then X(y)(ω) else 0)` on `(x, x + δ)` for sufficiently small `δ`, and use the right-continuity of this latter function.\n\nBut the actual proof might be easier: because `X(· and τ n)(ω)` is right-continuous and for `y < τ n ω`, `X(y and τ n)(ω) = X(y)(ω)`, then for `P`-a.e. `ω`, since `τ n ω → ∞`, we can take `n` such that `x < τ n ω` and `y < τ n ω` in a neighborhood of `x`.\n\nBut we need to pass from the right-continuity of the stopped process to that of the original process. \n\nAlternatively, since the stopped process is right-continuous, then for `x < τ n ω`, if we take `y ∈ (x, x + ε)` with `y < τ n ω`, the limit of `X(y)(ω)` as `y → x+` must equal `X(x)(ω)`, because `(y)(ω) = (y and τ n)(ω)` and the stopped process is right-continuous. But this only works if `x` is not the supremum of `{y < τ n ω}`. \n\n### Step 6: The Proof Approach\n\nThe standard approach is to note that the limit of the stopped process is the original process:\n\n`X = lim_{n → ∞} X ^ (τ n)`.\n\nBut `X ^ (τ n)` is right-continuous (in `x`) for each `n`. However, `τ n (ω)` tends to infinity as `n → ∞`, which allows us to find for every fixed `x` an `n` large enough so that `x < τ n (ω)` and work with the right continuity of `X ^ (τ n)`.\n\nHowever, the convergence is not uniform, and we need to be careful because even if `X ^ (τ n)` is right-continuous, it does not imply that the limit is right-continuous unless we have uniformity or some other condition.\n\nBut perhaps, because we work with a stopping time that goes to infinity, we can show that the constraint is only for a finite `n`, and we can then use right continuity of `X ^ (τ n)` to get the result.\n\n### Step 7: Formal Proof Outline\n\nWe will extract from `hX` the localizing sequence `τ n`, and deduce that:\n1. For each `n`, `X ^ (τ n)` is right-continuous in `x` for every `ω`.\n2. For `P`-a.e. `ω`, `τ n (ω) → ∞`.\n\nNow, for fixed `ω` where `τ n (ω) → ∞`, and any `x`, there exists `N` such that `x < τ n (ω)` for all `n ≥ N`.\n\nThen, for `n = N`, `X(y)(ω) = X ^ (τ N)(ω)(y)` for all `y ≤ x + ε`, if `x + ε < τ N (ω)`.\n\nThus, because `X ^ (τ N)` is right-continuous, `X(y)(ω)` is also right-continuous for `y ≤ x + ε`.\n\nTaking small `ε`, we can show that `X(·)(ω)` must be right-continuous at `x`.\n\nBut we need to perform an a.e. argument, because the sequence `τ n` is constructed so that `∀ n, ∀ ω, right_continuous (X ^ (τ n) · ω)`, but we want to deduce `∀ᵐ ω, right_continuous (X · ω)`.\n\n### Step 8: Actual Lean Proof Approach\n\nHowever, we can observe that:\n1. The localizing sequence can be of the form `τ n = n`, because it is always possible to take `τ n = n` (if we can assume that `X` is a.s. right-continuous at every rational).\n\nBut perhaps not because `X` could not be right-continuous anywhere. \n\nBut maybe the problem was constructed in such way that `hX` actually follows from some `Classical` assumption that everything is measurable and so on. \n\nAlternatively, perhaps in Lean's `ProbabilityTheory.Locally`, the `isLocalizingSequence` already gives us enough to deduce the result. \n\nBut perhaps it's easier to think that because of `Classical` reasoning and because of the right continuity of the stopped process, we can conclude that the original process is right-continuous. \n\n### Step 9: The Lean Proof via `Classical.choice`\n\nPerhaps in Lean,",
